I"ˇ<p>This tutorial will allow you to enable tear free video for both videos played locally and videos played from the browser.  I have previously needed to utilize the TearFree option when configuring Linux laptops.</p>

<hr />

<h5 id="xorg-configuration">Xorg Configuration:</h5>

<p>The SNA acceleration method causes tearing for some people. To fix this, enable the ‚ÄúTearFree‚Äù option in the driver by adding the following line to your configuration file:</p>

<p>nano /etc/X11/xorg.conf.d/20-intel.conf</p>

<p>Modify the configuration file appropriately, adding the TearFree Option as shown below:</p>

<div style="height: 200px; width: 675px; border: 1px solid #cccccc; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; font-weight: normal; line-height: 26px; font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal; overflow: auto;">
<div class="sites-codeblock sites-codesnippet-block">
<code>Section "Device"</code><br />
<code>Identifier  "Intel Graphics"</code><br />
<code>Driver      "intel"</code><br />
<code>Option "TearFree" "true"</code><br />
<code>EndSection</code><br />
</div>
</div>

<h5 id="firefox-configuration-optional">Firefox Configuration (optional):</h5>

<p>Previously, force enabling hardware acceleration in Firefox was necessary.  Only enable this if you are noticing an issue in FireFox after enabling TearFree for the Intel driver.</p>

<p>Type about:config into the address bar in Firefox</p>

<p>Search for layers.acceleration.force-enabled</p>

<p>Change the Value from false to true</p>

<p>Restart Firefox</p>
